By using the Cumulocity Web SDK, developers can leverage the functionality of the Cumulocity
platform and build custom web solutions tailored to their specific IoT use-cases.

The SDK provides a convenient way to handle authentication, data fetching and data visualization,
allowing developers to focus on building the core features of their applications.

The Cumulocity Web SDK uses [Angular](https://angular.io) as its main framework and the
Angular tool-set for development. You can get all Web SDK libraries via npm under the `@c8y`
scope.

**Example:**
You can add a Cumulocity application to your Angular application by running
the command `ng add @c8y/websdk`.

## Scaffolding your application

To start, create a default Angular application. You must ensure that you scaffold the right
Angular version. The following table shows an overview of the supported versions:

| Angular version | Web SDK version | Comment |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 18.x.x | 1021.x.x | No support for the standalone flag |
| 17.x.x | 1020.x.x | No support for the standalone flag |
| 16.x.x | 1019.x.x | Using [Angular CLI tooling](https://angular.io/cli). |
| 15.x.x | 1018.1.x - 1018.x.x | Using `c8ycli` tooling, only yearly release |
| 14.x.x | 1016.x.x - 1018.0.x | Using `c8ycli` tooling |

First, install the `@angular/cli` in the right version.

```bash
npx @angular/cli@v18 new --style=less
```

Second, change into the folder and add the `@c8y/websdk` package to your Angular application:

```bash
ng add @c8y/websdk
```

> ### Requirements
>  
> Requirement is a node.js installation. If you have the wrong node.js version installed, the
> `npm install` step will prompt you with the needed version number.

The CLI will prompt you in 2 simple steps for the version and the base template.

### Step 1: Select the version

```bash
? Which base version do you want to scaffold from? (Use arrow keys)
> 1019.0.X
> 1019.X.0
> other
```

In the second step, the base scaffolding version must be selected. The interface will provide the
last the latest available release. Additionally, you can manually enter a version by selecting the
`other` option. If you do not know which version to select, we recommend to use the latest.

### Step 2: Select the base project

```bash
? Which base project do you want to scaffold from?
  administration
  application
  cockpit
  devicemanagement
  hybrid
  tutorial
  sample-plugin
  package-blueprint
```
In step two, you must select the base project to scaffold from. You can select any of the default
Cumulocity applications to reuse the functions provided there. Alternatively, you can start a
blank application by selecting them _"application"_ project. For a complete list of all applications provided
see [Extendable applications](#/getting-started/library/overview#c8yapps-extendable-applications).

### Step 3: Start the local development server

Start the application by running the `npm start` command. By default, the
application will proxy to the Cumulocity cloud platform, however, you can proxy to a different
application using the `-u` flag. For example:

```bash
npm start -- -u http://mytenant.acme.iot
```

When started, the application begins to compile. After it is compiled, you can navigate to
`http://localhost:4200/apps/<<your-app-name>>/` and login to your tenant.

> #### Note
>  
> You need your tenant-id, username and password to login. You can find your tenant-id under
> platform information when you click on your username.

You are now setup.

Any changes you make to your local files will lead to recompiling. After a
refresh you will see your changes. Read more about the `@c8y` library setup and learn how to use
them in the next section.

## Create your first custom component

After creating the empty bootstrapping application you can start to add your content.
To do so, add a new component in the `src/app` to your project and save it as `hello.component.ts`:

```typescript
import { Component } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-hello',
  template: `
    <c8y-title>Hello World</c8y-title>
    <p>My first content.</p>
  `
})
export class HelloComponent {}
```

To hook the new component into the application, you have to declare the new component and add it to
a route in the `app.module.ts`. In the following example the `application` project is extended,
which gives you a very clear application frame.

```typescript
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { BrowserAnimationsModule } from '@angular/platform-browser/animations';
import { RouterModule as ngRouterModule } from '@angular/router';
import { CoreModule, BootstrapComponent } from '@c8y/ngx-components';
import { HelloComponent } from './hello.component';

@NgModule({
  imports: [
    BrowserAnimationsModule,
    ngRouterModule.forRoot(
      [{ path: '', component: HelloComponent }], // hook the route here
      { enableTracing: false, useHash: true }
    ),
    CoreModule.forRoot()
  ],
  bootstrap: [BootstrapComponent],
  declarations: [HelloComponent] // add deceleration here
})
export class AppModule {}
```

If you start this application and login, you see an application similar to the following:

<div class="c8y-example">
<img alt="Hello world app" src="data:image/png;base64,">
</div>

The application uses a customized router from the Web SDK and the `CoreModule`. The `CoreModule`
contains all the necessary components, directives, pipes and services that allow you to
[extend](#/getting-started/guides/extension-points) the application even further. However, first you must release the application and deploy it.

## Deploying your application

The CLI provides a command to deploy the application. To deploy your current application run the command `c8ycli deploy`. Before deploying your application you have to
build it. To build your application run the `c8ycli build` command.

For deployment, your application needs an application role, username, password and a tenant. You can also run it by
providing this information as parameters. The following will build and deploy the application
without prompting:

```bash
ng deploy -- -u http://yourtenant.cumulocity.com -T t12345 -U acme -P "*******"
```

In this example we use the custom deploy command added to Angular. You have to provide the option
`-T` (tenant), `-U` (user) and `-P` (password) to authenticate on your tenant. The deploy command
also accepts environment variables if you do not want to store them, prefixed with `C8Y_`. So for
example `C8Y_USER` for the `-U` flag.
